{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611430"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16212"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16212"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0,0.77,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115383"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97386"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"10647"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21399"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115383"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESupernumerary nipples are a common developmental variation that occurs during embryonic development (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical presentation of a supernumerary nipple?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A collection of breast tissue without a nipple","A fully formed breast with lactating capability","A small, pigmented spot along the embryonic milk line","A raised lesion occurring only on the chest wall","An unpigmented patch occurring randomly on the body"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall, pigmented spot along the embryonic milk line\u003C/strong\u003E is the typical presentation of a supernumerary nipple. These accessory nipples develop along the embryonic milk lines, which extend from the axilla to the groin bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA fully formed breast with lactating capability\u003C/strong\u003E is not typical as while some supernumerary nipples may have associated breast tissue, most are rudimentary and lack functional capability. \u003Cstrong\u003EA raised lesion occurring only on the chest wall\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since supernumerary nipples can occur anywhere along the milk line, not just on the chest wall. \u003Cstrong\u003EAn unpigmented patch occurring randomly on the body\u003C/strong\u003E does not describe supernumerary nipples as they are typically pigmented and follow the milk lines rather than occurring randomly. \u003Cstrong\u003EA collection of breast tissue without a nipple\u003C/strong\u003E describes accessory breast tissue which can occur without a nipple, but this is not the typical presentation of a supernumerary nipple.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESupernumerary nipples are present in approximately 1% of the population and are often mistaken for moles or nevi. They represent a benign developmental variation and rarely require treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Supernumerary nipples occur along the embryonic milk lines and are present in approximately 1% of the population.","Supernumerary nipples typically appear as small, pigmented spots that may be mistaken for moles or nevi.","The embryonic milk lines extend from the axilla to the groin bilaterally."],"references":["Sperduto W, McCullough A, Northfelt D, McGee L, Pockaj B, Jogerst K. Implications of a Supernumerary Nipple Breast Cancer in a BReast CAncer Sequence Variation Carrier: A Case Report. Mayo Clin Proc Innov Qual Outcomes. 2023 Sep 20;7(5):437-442. doi: 10.1016/j.mayocpiqo.2023.08.006. PMID: 37752967; PMCID: PMC10518438.","Zucca-Matthes G, Urban C, Vallejo A. Anatomy of the nipple and breast ducts. Gland Surg. 2016 Feb;5(1):32-6. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2227-684X.2015.05.10. PMID: 26855906; PMCID: PMC4716863","Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97386"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16212"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21230"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21230"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4KMOYNWjjDLNePLLPFAYqo3yJyUK3Z.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4KMOYNWjjDLNePLLPFAYqo3yJyUK3Z.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":308,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97386"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:22:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:23:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8903"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115383"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t